ce:section.ce:para:
Initially, the η of the waveguide medium with a flat-bottom structure was investigated. As illustrated in Fig. 4c–f, the fluorescence layer emitted 100 uniformly distributed rays at each emission event, with the φ of the emitted fluorescence set to 0°, 30°, 41.8°, and 45° for Fig. 4c, 4d, 4e, and 4f, respectively. For an optical waveguide medium with a refractive index of 1.5, the critical angle for total internal reflection was approximately 41.8°. When the φ was less than 41.8°, fluorescence escape occurred; however, when φ was greater than or equal to 41.8°, total internal reflection was achieved, causing the fluorescence to remain within the waveguide medium. Further simulation results revealed that when the φ of the emitted fluorescence was 0°, the corresponding η was 0 % (Fig. 4g), indicating that no light emitted by the CDs could be absorbed by the HPSC. As the φ increased, the η also improved, with a clear correlation between φ and η (Fig. 4g–j). When the φ was greater than or equal to 41.8°, the η reached 100 % (Fig. 4i and 4j). Based on these simulation results, the average light gathering efficiency (ηavg.
                        ) of the waveguide medium was calculated for incident angles ranging from 0° to 90°, without altering the waveguide structure. This yielded an overall ηavg.
                         of 61.5 %.
